const blocks = [
  { type: 'text', content: "Samburu is for travelers who love the feeling of finding something rare. North of Mount Kenya, the road climbs out of the greener highlands and drops toward a drier, more sculptural landscape: ochre earth, long views, doum palms, rocky kopjes, and the steady green ribbon of the <strong>Ewaso Nyiro River</strong>." },
  { type: 'text', content: "The reserve is not as famous as the Maasai Mara, and that is part of its charm. Game drives feel intimate. The light is crisp. Wildlife gathers around the river with a sense of theatre, and the dry-country species give Samburu a personality that feels completely different from southern Kenya." },
  { type: 'quote', content: "Samburu is where Kenya's safari map changes texture: rarer wildlife, quieter game drives, dramatic dry-country scenery, and a river that pulls the whole ecosystem together." },
  { type: 'image', src: '/images/giraffes-savanna-safari-simbali-wild-safaris.jpg', alt: 'Reticulated giraffes in a dry savannah landscape', caption: "Samburu's reticulated giraffes are among the most elegant and photogenic of the northern species." },
  { type: 'h2', content: 'Why Samburu Feels Different' },
  { type: 'text', content: "Samburu sits in Kenya's rugged northern frontier, an area shaped by heat, water scarcity, pastoral cultures, and wildlife beautifully adapted to arid conditions. The reserve itself covers a compact area compared with some headline parks, but its habitats are varied: riverine forest, acacia scrub, open plains, seasonal streams, and rocky hills that catch the evening light." },
  { type: 'text', content: "The Ewaso Nyiro River is the heartbeat. In the dry season, it becomes a gathering place for elephants, antelope, baboons, leopards, crocodiles, kingfishers, bee-eaters, and countless smaller signs of life. A good guide will read the riverbank like a page: fresh elephant tracks, alarm calls, dust movement, the direction of grazing, and the sudden silence that can reveal a predator nearby." },
  { type: 'note', label: 'Safari Fit', content: "Samburu works beautifully for travelers who want a safari that feels exclusive without being stiff: fewer vehicles, strong guiding, rare species, and a sense of discovery before continuing to Ol Pejeta, Lake Naivasha, or the Maasai Mara." },
  { type: 'h2', content: 'Meet the Special Five' },
  { type: 'text', content: "Samburu is famous for the <strong>Special Five</strong>, a group of dry-country animals that make northern Kenya feel distinct. They are not a marketing gimmick; they are a genuine expression of place, shaped by the climate and vegetation of this region." },
  { type: 'list', items: [
    "<strong>Grevy's zebra:</strong> taller and more refined than the plains zebra, with narrow stripes, a white belly, rounded ears, and an endangered conservation status.",
    "<strong>Reticulated giraffe:</strong> instantly recognizable by its clean white lines and rich chestnut patches, often seen browsing thorn trees in soft morning light.",
    "<strong>Somali ostrich:</strong> blue-necked males and grey-brown females stride across the open country, especially in drier areas.",
    "<strong>Gerenuk:</strong> the long-necked antelope that stands upright on its hind legs to browse, looking almost impossibly delicate.",
    "<strong>Beisa oryx:</strong> elegant desert antelope with long spear-like horns and a mask-like face pattern.",
  ]},
  { type: 'image', src: '/images/free-use-grevys-zebra-pixabay.jpg', alt: "Grevy's zebra profile showing narrow stripes and large rounded ears", caption: "Grevy's zebra is one of Samburu's great conservation highlights and a signature Special Five sighting. Free-use photo from Pixabay." },
  { type: 'h2', content: 'Elephants Along the Ewaso Nyiro' },
  { type: 'text', content: "Elephants give Samburu its emotional weight. Herds move down to the river in the heat of the day, calves tucked into the shade of their mothers, older females testing the water, young bulls splashing with theatrical confidence. Because the reserve is relatively compact, sightings can feel close and unhurried when handled with patience and respect." },
  { type: 'text', content: "Samburu's elephants are part of a wider northern Kenya movement system. They travel between community lands, conservancies, river corridors, and protected areas. That makes every sighting more than a beautiful photograph: it is a reminder that safari landscapes only work when wildlife has space beyond park boundaries." },
  { type: 'image', src: '/images/elephant-herd-waterhole-safari-simbali-wild-safaris.jpg', alt: 'Elephant herd gathered near water', caption: "Water shapes Samburu wildlife behavior, especially in the dry season when elephants gather along river corridors." },
  { type: 'h2', content: 'Predators, Birdlife and Small Details' },
  { type: 'text', content: "Samburu is excellent predator country. Lions patrol the plains and river edges, leopards use the riverine trees and rocky cover, and cheetahs can appear in more open areas. Spotted hyenas, jackals, crocodiles, and raptors complete the drama, but the reserve also rewards slower looking." },
  { type: 'text', content: "Birders can expect a strong mix of dry-country and riverine species: vulturine guineafowl, secretary birds, hornbills, bee-eaters, rollers, kingfishers, eagles, sandgrouse, and weavers. Even guests who do not travel as birdwatchers often leave Samburu surprised by the color and movement in the trees." },
  { type: 'image', src: '/images/raptor-bird-flying-clear-sky_blog.jpg', alt: 'Raptor flying against clear sky', caption: "Northern Kenya is rich in raptors, and Samburu's open skies make birds of prey easier to follow." },
  { type: 'h2', content: 'The Best Game Drive Rhythm' },
  { type: 'text', content: "Early mornings are for cool air, tracks, predators returning from the night, and golden light catching the palms. Midday belongs to the river: elephants drinking, crocodiles resting, birds moving through shade. Late afternoon brings warmth back into the colors, with long shadows across the plains and the possibility of predators becoming active again." },
  { type: 'list', items: [
    "<strong>Morning:</strong> look for fresh tracks, lions on the move, leopards returning to cover, and Special Five species feeding before the heat rises.",
